[
    {
        "content": "<p>Does anyone know a reference for the fact that the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Cauchy+complete+category\">Cauchy completion</a> of a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span></span></span></span> enriched over vector spaces is formed by taking the full subcategory of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Vect</span></span></span></span></span>-valued presheaves on  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span></span></span></span> consisting of retracts of finite coproducts of representables?</p>",
        "id": 368042836,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1687291592
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If worst comes to worst, I'll settle for a reference for the analogous fact with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Vect</span></span></span></span></span> replaced by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Ab}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Ab</span></span></span></span></span>.   Even the oldest sources I've looked at seem to take this for granted.</p>",
        "id": 368043075,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1687291667
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As far as I know (and you probably know this too), this notion of Cauchy completion for enriched categories was first defined by Lawvere in his 1973 paper \"Metric spaces, generalized logic, and closed categories\", where he claims that \"it can be shown\" that the characterization you mention holds for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Ab}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Ab</span></span></span></span></span>, making it the bad sort of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/folklore\">[[folklore]]</a>.  It seems like someone in the intervening 50 years ought to have written out a proof, but I don't know of one.</p>\n<p>The closest I can find right now is in <a href=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/volumes/37/28/37-28abs.html\">Cauchy completeness for DG-categories</a> by Nikolić, Street, and Tendas (2021), they show (Prop 6.1) that the Cauchy completion of a category enriched over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>-graded abelian groups is formed by taking the full subcategory of enriched presheaves (\"right modules\") consisting of retracts of finite coproducts of <em>suspensions of</em> representables.  Inspecting the proof, it's clear that the grading could be by any abelian group instead of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>, and taking it to be the trivial group yields the result for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Ab}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Ab</span></span></span></span></span>.  But surely there must be an earlier and better reference than that.</p>",
        "id": 368070935,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1687302745
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I do not know any earlier references, but that result could be seen as a consequence of Prop 4.23 (see also 4.22) of my paper <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2107.08612\">Flat vs. filtered colimits in the enriched context</a>, joint with Lack.  There, among other things, we characterize Cauchy completions for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>-categories enriched over, what we call, a \"locally dualizable\" base; the main point being that such a base has a strong generator <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span> made of dualizable objects. <br>\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Vect</span></span></span></span></span> is an example of these, and the strong generator <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span> is given by the unit; therefore the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span>-copowers  used in Prop. 4.23 are trivial (i.e. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P\\cdot \\mathcal C(-,C)\\cong \\mathcal C(-,C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⋅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> in the statement). Using that the absolute=Cauchy weights are the objects of the Cauchy completion, this gives the result you wanted.</p>",
        "id": 368161983,
        "sender_full_name": "Giacomo",
        "timestamp": 1687337947
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Cauchy.20complete.20linear.20categories/near/368070935\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>As far as I know (and you probably know this too), this notion of Cauchy completion for enriched categories was first defined by Lawvere in his 1973 paper \"Metric spaces, generalized logic, and closed categories\", where he claims that \"it can be shown\" that the characterization you mention holds for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Ab}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Ab</span></span></span></span></span>, making it the bad sort of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/folklore\">[[folklore]]</a>.  It seems like someone in the intervening 50 years ought to have written out a proof, but I don't know of one.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, I tracked the thread of references back and reached this point!  It was sort of like pulling on a long fishing line and after a long struggle finding I'd caught nothing.</p>",
        "id": 368259097,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1687358008
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"626639\">Giacomo</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Cauchy.20complete.20linear.20categories/near/368161983\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I do not know any earlier references, but that result could be seen as a consequence of Prop 4.23 (see also 4.22) of my paper <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2107.08612\">Flat vs. filtered colimits in the enriched context</a>, joint with Lack.  There, among other things, we characterize Cauchy completions for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>-categories enriched over, what we call, a \"locally dualizable\" base; the main point being that such a base has a strong generator <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span> made of dualizable objects. <br>\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Vect}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Vect</span></span></span></span></span> is an example of these, and the strong generator <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span> is given by the unit; therefore the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span>-copowers  used in Prop. 4.23 are trivial (i.e. <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≅</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P\\cdot \\mathcal C(-,C)\\cong \\mathcal C(-,C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⋅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> in the statement). Using that the absolute=Cauchy weights are the objects of the Cauchy completion, this gives the result you wanted.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Thanks!   Since I really need the result for Vect rather than Ab, this will do the job quite nicely!  </p>\n<p>I was also curious about it for RMod for an arbitrary commutative ring, and I guess this too has a strong generator given by the unit R, which is dualizable.</p>",
        "id": 368260439,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1687358241
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In Proposition 4.22 you say a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{V}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>-category is Cauchy complete iff it has finite direct sums, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{G}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span>-copowers, and splitting of idempotents.    This sounds like a very practical criterion, but I don't see where you define \"has <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{G}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span>-copowers\" - the phrase first shows up in Remark 4.11.  Is the idea that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{G}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span> is an arbitrary strong generator consisting of dualizable objects?  Did you fix such a set somewhere?</p>",
        "id": 368353325,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1687378729
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, I don't really know what it means for a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{V}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>-category to have \"finite direct sums\".    Are these biproducts?   Is there a way to define biproducts at this level of generality?   I know how to do it if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{V}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> has a zero object.</p>",
        "id": 368355913,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1687379555
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Regardig <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span>, it is part of Defn 4.3 where we give the hypotheses on the base of enrichment; and yes, you can take it to be any strong generator made of dualizable objects. By saying that a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span>-category has <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span>-copowers we simply mean that it has copowers by objects in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span> (maybe the notation is not as standard as I thought). Then, the equivalence <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>⇔</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(2)\\Leftrightarrow (3)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇔</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">3</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> in 4.22 says that it doesn't really matter what strong generator you choose at the beginning: you are always getting all copowers by dualizable objects.<br>\nAbout finite direct sums. Yes, I mean biproducts (but I personally don't like the name, as it makes me think about the \"weak\" 2-limits). A quick way to define them would be to say that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">V</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal V</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">V</span></span></span></span> is enriched over commutative monoids and has finite coproducts. Which is equivalent to  saying that it has a zero object and binary biproducts (as they are usually defined in the additive context).</p>",
        "id": 368448227,
        "sender_full_name": "Giacomo",
        "timestamp": 1687418698
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, thanks very much!  I understood the term \"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{G}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span>-copowers\" for some arbitrary set of objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{G}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span>, but I had trouble quickly finding where you assert your standing hypotheses on this set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{G}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7805em;vertical-align:-0.0972em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0593em;\">G</span></span></span></span> (or on your base of enrichment).   I see now that Definition 4.3 has what I want.</p>\n<p>I put some of this information into the nLab article <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Cauchy%20complete%20category\">[[Cauchy complete category]]</a>.</p>",
        "id": 368579118,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1687443776
    }
